 succeeded in 0ms:
     1	# SQLAlchemy 2 Cutover
     2	
     3	This cutover removes legacy helper-level commits and moves transaction control to
     4	the API, worker, and admin command boundaries. Repository reads use SQLAlchemy
     5	2-style `select(...)` statements so helper access stays side-effect free while
     6	the call sites decide when to commit or rollback.
     7	
     8	## Recovery Expectations
     9	
    10	- A failed worker retry must rollback the transient `processing` mark and leave
    11	  the row at `pending`.
    12	- Admin dry-run flows must stay read-only and must not queue rows.
    13	- Batch failures must rollback the whole in-flight command so retry state does
    14	  not leak across entries.
    15	
    16	## Rollout Checks
    17	
    18	Before release, run `pytest -q tests/test_api.py tests/test_worker.py
    19	tests/test_admin_cli.py` and confirm:
    20	
    21	- API writes can participate in an outer transaction without closing it early.
    22	- Forced worker failures recover to `pending`.
    23	- Admin dry-runs leave existing rows unchanged.
    24	
    25	## Rollback Notes
    26	
    27	If rollback is required during deployment, stop new worker/admin traffic first,
    28	redeploy the prior build, and verify impacted rows are back to `pending` before
    29	re-enabling retries. The prior incident was caused by retry-state leakage from
    30	helper-owned commits, so operator verification should focus on clearing any
    31	stranded `processing` or accidentally `queued` rows before resuming traffic.

